snippet.textDisplay:
First off, look at Italy. Their infection rate is more than 10 times the US's. There are reasons for that other than measures taken early on, BUT.


Late January, Italian health authorities (the experts) proposed isolating thousands of workers who'd arrived and were continuing to arrive from the epicenter (Wuhan), and from other areas in China. That proposal was deemed "racist" and rejected by government officials (the politicians).


Still, news was pouring into the country--including news of Trump's travel restrictions (and similar in Russia and Israel). Anyone paying attention would have thought, "hmmmm.... maybe this is serious and I should take my own individual measures."


I mean, I did. I still bought from our local Chinese restaurant, because they're an awesome, family-run place. The food is great, and they accommodate my husband's dietary restrictions from memory. When I call and give my address, doesn't matter who answers the phone, they'll say, "ahh... for Karen...? Curry beef, no milk, no onion, no soy for Michael?" But, even more importantly right now, I know they don't travel. If they did, they'd have to close, and they don't close.


And my local dollar store. Same thing--owned and operated by a husband and wife who immigrated from China decades ago. They're the only workers there, and they haven't been closed in years. So. They don't travel to China.


If I knew they'd travelled recently, I'd avoid them for a while--not because they're Chinese, but because they had travelled. Like 9 of the Chinese workers in my husband's open concept office of 150 people did in December. Frankly, given how sick my husband and I got in January (and how sick Fong got too after returning), for all I know, we've already had it and recovered. But still.


Anyway.


In January, the mayor of Florence had noticed the locals were keeping their distance from the Chinese. I suspect they were doing what I was doing--if you're a longstanding member of my community who happens to be Chinese, and haven't recently travelled to China, cool. If you're Chinese and I don't know anything about you, that's a whole different ballgame.


He wanted to do something to combat this "racism", so from Feb 1 to at least Feb 4, he promoted "Hug a Chinese Day" on social media. He literally encouraged citizens of Florence (in northern Italy, which is now the hardest hit) to walk up to random Chinese strangers and hug them. Now the Italian health system is rationing ventilators, endotracheal tubes, masks and medicines. They don't have sufficient personnel to take care of all the sick. And as they force their health care staff to work double and triple shifts to accommodate the huge number of sick who are sick all at the same time, those workers will--from fatigue and stress, shortages of protective gear, and constant exposure to high viral loads--become more vulnerable to infection.


What happens when health workers in Italy start becoming infected and dying en masse?


Because of that triage-based rationing, their case fatality rate last week was 8% (the US's was 1.7%) and they have one of the highest per capita infection rates in the world (886 confirmed cases per 1m population, vs 82 per 1m in the US).


The US is attempting to avoid the positive feedback loop that Italy is suffering right now.


There have been several bills put in place to attempt to provide small businesses with low interest loans to allow owners to keep staff on payroll even while closed. Unemployment insurance is being leveraged and streamlined to compensate laid off workers. Other short term measures are in effect, such as delaying the deadline to file income tax until summer. And costs for manufacturing and transport of goods are way down, due to the tanking oil prices (thanks Russia and Saudi Arabia!).


Markets are stabilizing as people like me (who have a little money I can live without for a while) see an opportunity to buy shares in companies with good, long-term prospects at very low prices. Bonds will probably be offered if they haven't already. The administration has arranged for private sector involvement, such as 3M retrofitting their factories to begin producing masks, and auto plants starting to manufacture respirators. This is vital, since China is where we used to get all of that stuff, and China stopped exporting masks in January because they needed their entire manufacturing capacity (and then some) to deal with the outbreak in Hubei.


This is a wake-up call regarding how the west has allowed one country that isn't fond of us to corner the market on medical supplies and equipment, and pharmaceuticals and their base ingredients. I predict the administration will take the US from almost total dependence on China to national independence (the way it did with oil and gas).


And, to the wonder of us all, Governors Cuomo and Newsom (both Dems) have praised the administration's nonpartisan commitment to assisting NY and CA with their outbreaks. Erstwhile enemies are working together against this common foe. And that might, in the end, turn out to be priceless.

I got sick 3 months ago in what I thought was a flu. My chest was congested, fever, runny nose, and a nasty cough that was so strong it would make me throw up and I had pain in my ribs that's how strong the cough was, I could barely sleep.
This continued for about 3 weeks until finally I started to feel better. But two weeks after that I was still coughing only now it was a dry cough, not wet like before. Now I feel fine but I'm wondering if it was COVID19 since I'm sure it was around back then we just weren't aware. I've had the flu before but this was just extra I never felt so miserable physically. IDK but...🤔🤔🤔
